>>34817129
Here is the actual answer, and it’s not a pleasant one.
Write every day, even if you don’t want to. I’m a writer who knows exactly how things are going to turn out, and all that matters to me is getting everything down on paper. This is the hard part. Writing to me is not fun, it is a grueling, cumbersome slog, and I suffered from mental breakdowns after finishing a few of them.
However, I said write every day, not a lot. The shortest acceptable length for a novel is 60k. An average length is 70-90k. If you wrote 500 words a day, that would be around 15k words in a month. In less than five months you would have a novel length story. Most people here will not write something that big. Most of the time it’s going to be 15k or less. 500 words is the page long essay your 6th grade teacher would make you write. It’s not very long.
>But what if I’m uninspired and write something that’s shit?
So what? Go back and fix it when the story, or that chapter, or update/whatever is finished. You don’t stop writing because you don’t feel like it, and you especially don’t go back and start revisions until the thing is done. Because then you’ll get nothing done and you’ll be the family member at the reunions going on for the next decade about a book he never finishes. Don’t be that guy. That guy is a fucking loser. If that means you wrote a 30k story for the general and it’s fucking crap and you need to fix it, then so be it. At the very least you have a skeleton you can work from, a finished product that you can look at and be proud of, regardless of the flaws.

People rarely finish anything they start. Our brains are too fried by phones and the internet and video games. I promise you; I fucking promise you that if you just power through the writers’ block and just start typing shit down, even if its total garbage you’ll be happy with yourself because you did something that probably less than 1% of the global population can do.
